##Chapter 4: The Beginning of Multi-Layered Reality: A Portrait
Imagine you are standing in front of a disturbing portrait in an art gallery. The person in the painting has hollow eyes, a twisted mouth, and the colors feel suffocating — like something from a nightmare. You start to shiver. A cold feeling runs through you.

You know it's just a painting. It's not alive.

Yet your body and emotions react as if it were real. You feel fear.

Is this real? Or just your imagination?

From this simple experience, we begin a deeper journey to understand what "reality" means. This is not only about the painting — it's about how we understand ourselves and our relationship with the universe.



4.1　Four Layers of Reality: How the Mind Filters and Creates Experience
To understand how this painting can affect you so deeply, we can look at it through four different layers of reality. Each layer shows us something true — but in a different way. These layers are not in conflict. Instead, they add up to form a complete experience.
And most importantly, in each of these layers, your mind plays an active role — not just seeing reality, but filtering it, interpreting it, and even creating it.


The First Layer — Rational View: Just Particles?
From the most purely scientific view, the painting is just a group of atoms. The paint molecules stick to the canvas. Light reflects off the surface, enters your eyes, sends signals to your brain, and creates the experience of “seeing."

Science tells us: this is just the interaction of light, matter, and your nervous system.

But is this the full story of what you're experiencing? If reality is only this, how do we explain your fear? This layer shows the basic material structure, but it cannot explain meaning, emotion, or the feeling of being scared.


The Second Layer — Physical View: A Real Object
Looking at it another way, the painting is a physical thing. It has weight, a location on the wall, and can be measured. This is the most familiar level of reality — something we can see and touch.

But still, this doesn't explain why it scares you. Even though the painting exists in the physical world, its physical features do not contain fear by themselves. We begin to see something important: reality is not just about "what exists," but also about how it is experienced and interpreted.


The Third Layer — Cognitive View: Who Is in the Painting?
What you see is not just paint or canvas. You see a face — a person. Maybe he looks in pain, or lost, or broken. Your brain quickly turns these lines and colors into a story, a character, maybe even a suffering soul. You are not looking at a painting anymore. You are meeting someone, feeling something.

Here we discover the power of perception. The face is not physically there — it is something your brain creates based on the signals from your eyes and your own life experiences.

Our senses are natural filters. Human eyes can only see a small range of light. Our ears only hear certain sound frequencies. This means our reality is always filtered before we even begin to think about it. Then your brain interprets these limited signals based on your beliefs, past experiences, and expectations.

Two people can look at the same painting and feel totally different emotions — not because the painting changed, but because their inner filters are different. Reality becomes personal, shaped by the mind's unique interpretation.


The Fourth Layer — Spiritual View: Are You Seeing Yourself?
If you stare at the painting long enough, something strange may happen. You stop focusing on the painting — and start feeling yourself. The fear, the sadness, or the loneliness you feel might not come from the painting, but from inside you. The painting becomes a mirror. You are no longer observing the artwork — you are observing yourself.

This is the spiritual layer of reality. What you experience says more about your inner world than about the painting. Maybe this is what philosophy, religion, art, and even cosmology have always pointed to: your inner landscape is the ultimate filter through which you perceive reality.



4.2　Four Layers, One Reality: From a Painting to the Universe
So the painting is real in all four layers. At the particle level, it is made of atoms and molecules. At the physical level, it is a visible and touchable object. At the cognitive level, it is seen as a face, a person, an emotion. At the spiritual level, it reflects your own inner world.

These layers don't cancel each other out. They are different expressions of the same reality.

And in fact, we can view the entire universe in the same way. Some see the universe as a mathematical structure, made of numbers and equations. Others see it as physical matter, made of stars, dust, and energy. Some believe it is a mental projection, shaped by how our minds interpret the world. And some believe the universe is a spiritual field, where we grow, evolve, and awaken. These views are not in conflict. They are connected through the idea of emergence.

Emergence means: when simple parts combine in a complex way, new properties appear — like life, consciousness, or beauty. A painting's emotional power doesn't come from any single paint molecule. It emerges from the combination of color, form, and your mental and emotional interaction with it.

In daily life, we constantly choose which layer of reality to focus on. You don't think of a person as a walking skeleton or a collection of organs — otherwise, you could never fall in love. You choose to see them through the cognitive or spiritual layer, not the biological one.

In the same way, even if the universe is a limited and cyclical system, different layers can still give rise to rich and new experiences. Just like a few letters can form many poems, and a few notes can create countless melodies.

You and I — each human being — are examples of this. We are emergent beings, formed from tiny particles arranged in complex ways. And perhaps the consciousness of the universe itself is also an emergent reality, born from the interaction of all things at once.



4.3　Non-Infinity Theory Could Also Be Wrong
Let's return to the core idea of Non-Infinity Theory.

When we say a painting "has a soul," we don't actually believe it can speak. Instead, we project meaning and feeling onto it — adding something beyond its physical reality.

In the same way, here is a bold thought: Non-Infinity Theory could also be wrong.

Think about looking at a portrait — there can be many valid ways to interpret it at the same time. So when it comes to the debate between infinity and non-infinity, do we really need to choose just one side? The answer might be: we don't have to.

The idea of non-infinity has its own limits, just like infinity does. Even if our universe is finite, what surrounds this finite system? Is there a higher cycle? If we say the universe began from "nothing" and will return to "nothing," then that nothingness also has a beginning and an end — it is a kind of structure too.

So what if this back-and-forth between nothing and universe is just one layer in a much larger cycle? And what if that larger cycle also belongs to an even bigger system? The more we ask, the more we realize: no matter how we imagine a finite universe, we always end up needing a background to hold it. And that leads us into a paradox. If all finite things exist in cycles, and all cycles must be held within something bigger, then the final layer must be something that cannot be finite.

This leads to an interesting conclusion: infinity and non-infinity can both be right — and both be wrong — depending on which level of reality we are looking from. They are not enemies. They are different lenses through which we experience the same reality.

Non-Infinity Theory does not overthrow existing science, just as Einstein's relativity did not deny Newton's physics. It offers a higher-level view that helps us understand the concept of "infinity" as something the mind creates, rather than a true structure of nature. In most everyday and scientific situations, traditional math and physics still work perfectly well. But Non-Infinity Theory provides a deeper framework to explain why these systems appear to be infinite.

There is also a key point worth noting: our existence itself is a rejection of absolute nothingness. If the nothing before the universe were truly infinite, then something could never have come from it. But we do exist. This suggests that even "nothing" had some kind of boundary or shape — meaning it was not truly infinite. And if nothing isn't infinite, how can the universe that came from it be infinite?

When we say "the universe is infinite," could it actually be a kind of psychological projection? Maybe the feeling of infinity is just what happens when our mind faces something too large to understand — a kind of mental overload. Like the way we feel a portrait is "looking at us" even though it has no awareness, the idea that the universe is infinite might be a cognitive illusion, born from our inability to see the edges. This is the same kind of illusion we talked about in Chapter 1 with the waves.

So we should look at the infinity versus non-infinity question the way we look at a portrait — not in black-and-white terms, but through many layers at once.

This portrait exists as particles, as a physical object, as an emotional experience, and as a spiritual mirror. All of these are real, and none of them cancel each other out. This is the core message of Non-Infinity Theory: it doesn't deny infinity as a mental or mathematical tool. It simply suggests that the physical universe itself is likely finite and cyclical.

Infinity is a tool of human thought, existing in logic and math, used to describe things we cannot fully measure. Non-infinity points to the actual limits and cycles in the physical world. The two are not enemies — they are just different levels of reality. Like how the paint and canvas don't deny the face you see in a portrait, infinity as a concept does not conflict with a finite universe. We emphasize non-infinity only because humans tend to assume infinity exists simply because we haven't seen the limits yet.

Before we move on, take a moment to think: the fear you felt when looking at that portrait — was it real, or was it a story your mind created to fill in the gaps? If the answer is "both," then perhaps everything you believe about the universe deserves to be looked at the same way.
